title: Red Team DeepSeek
description: A Python-based tool for red teaming large language models, specifically DeepSeek. It allows users to engineer prompts with various attack strategies to test the model's vulnerabilities and robustness against malicious inputs. The tool logs the results to create a dataset for analyzing model performance and safety.

title: PerspectiveAPI Hate Speech Classification
description: A project that implements and evaluates different machine learning models for hate speech classification, using the PerspectiveAPI dataset. The project explores various text feature engineering techniques and compares the performance of models like Logistic Regression and Transformers.

title: Conversational RAG System
description: A full-stack conversational AI application using a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) architecture. The backend is built with Python, Flask, and LangChain, and the frontend is a responsive chat interface using HTML, and Tailwind CSS. It includes a feedback mechanism integrated with LangSmith for monitoring and improvement.

title: Privacy Analyzer (Prof P)
description: A Chrome Extension that helps users understand complex privacy policies by generating AI-powered summaries and calculating readability scores for highlighted text.

title: FoodConnect: Volunteer Coordination System
description: A volunteer management system designed for community food organizations, including food banks and food pantries. This application simplifies the process of volunteer sign-ups, tracking, and prioritization using a robust Java-based architecture.

title: Rubix
description: A speed-based mathematical puzzle game built with the Godot engine. The objective is to reach a randomly generated target number starting from zero. Players use four distinct operations (increment, decrement, multiply, divide), where the value of each operation increases with every use, adding a strategic layer to the challenge. The game tracks the player's completion time, encouraging fast and efficient problem-solving.
